# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: autothrottle
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] An **accelerometer** is a device that measures the proper acceleration of an object.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Proper acceleration is the acceleration (the rate of change of velocity) of the object relative to an observer who is in free fall (that is, relative to an inertial frame of reference).
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Proper acceleration is different from coordinate acceleration, which is acceleration with respect to a given coordinate system, which may or may not be accelerating.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] For example, an accelerometer at rest on the surface of the Earth will measure an acceleration due to Earth's gravity straight upwards of about *g* ≈ 9.81 m/s2.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] By contrast, an accelerometer that is in free fall will measure zero acceleration.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Highly sensitive accelerometers are used in inertial navigation systems for aircraft and missiles.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] In unmanned aerial vehicles, accelerometers help to stabilize flight.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Micromachined micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS) accelerometers are used in handheld electronic devices such as smartphones, cameras and video-game controllers to detect movement and orientation of these devices.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Vibration in industrial machinery is monitored by accelerometers.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Seismometers are sensitive accelerometers for monitoring ground movement such as earthquakes.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] When two or more accelerometers are coordinated with one another, they can measure differences in proper acceleration, particularly gravity, over their separation in space—that is, the gradient of the gravitational field.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Gravity gradiometry is useful because absolute gravity is a weak effect and depends on the local density of the Earth, which is quite variable.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] A single-axis accelerometer measures acceleration along a specified axis.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] A multi-axis accelerometer detects both the magnitude and the direction of the proper acceleration, as a vector quantity, and is usually implemented as several single-axis accelerometers oriented along different axes.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] An accelerometer measures proper acceleration, which is the acceleration it experiences relative to freefall and is the acceleration felt by people and objects.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Put another way, at any point in spacetime the equivalence principle guarantees the existence of a local inertial frame, and an accelerometer measures the acceleration relative to that frame.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Such accelerations are popularly denoted g-force; i.e., in comparison to standard gravity.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] An accelerometer at rest relative to the Earth's surface will indicate approximately 1 g *upwards* because the Earth's surface exerts a normal force upwards relative to the local inertial frame (the frame of a freely falling object near the surface).
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] To obtain the acceleration due to motion with respect to the Earth, this "gravity offset" must be subtracted and corrections made for effects caused by the Earth's rotation relative to the inertial frame.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] The reason for the appearance of a gravitational offset is Einstein's equivalence principle, which states that the effects of gravity on an object are indistinguishable from acceleration.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] When held fixed in a gravitational field by, for example, applying a ground reaction force or an equivalent upward thrust, the reference frame for an accelerometer (its own casing) accelerates upwards with respect to a free-falling reference frame.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] For similar reasons, an accelerometer will read *zero* during any type of free fall.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] This includes use in a coasting spaceship in deep space far from any mass, a spaceship orbiting the Earth, an airplane in a parabolic "zero-g" arc, or any free-fall in a vacuum.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Another example is free-fall at a sufficiently high altitude that atmospheric effects can be neglected.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] However, this does not include a (non-free) fall in which air resistance produces drag forces that reduce the acceleration until constant terminal velocity is reached.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] At terminal velocity, the accelerometer will indicate 1 g acceleration upwards.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] For the same reason a skydiver, upon reaching terminal velocity, does not feel as though he or she were in "free-fall", but rather experiences a feeling similar to being supported (at 1 g) on a "bed" of uprushing air.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Acceleration is quantified in the SI unit metres per second per second (m/s2), in the cgs unit gal (Gal), or popularly in terms of standard gravity (*g*).
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] For the practical purpose of finding the acceleration of objects with respect to the Earth, such as for use in an inertial navigation system, a knowledge of local gravity is required.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] This can be obtained either by calibrating the device at rest, or from a known model of gravity at the approximate current position.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] A basic mechanical accelerometer is a damped proof mass on a spring.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] When the accelerometer experiences an acceleration, Newton's third law causes the spring's compression (or extension) to adjust to exert an equivalent force on the mass to counteract the acceleration.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Since the spring's force scales linearly with the length change (according to Hooke's law) and because the spring constant and mass are known constants, a measurement of the spring's compression (or extension) is also a measurement of acceleration.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] The system is damped to prevent oscillations of the mass and spring interfering with measurements.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] However, the damping causes accelerometers to have a frequency response.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Many animals have sensory organs to detect acceleration, especially gravity.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] In these, the proof mass is usually one or more crystals of calcium carbonate otoliths (Latin for "ear stone") or statoconia, acting against a bed of hairs connected to neurons.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] The hairs form the springs, with the neurons as sensors.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Many vertebrates, including humans, have these structures in their inner ears.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Most invertebrates have similar organs, but not as part of their hearing organs.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Mechanical accelerometers are often designed so that an electronic circuit senses a small amount of motion, then pushes on the proof mass with some type of linear motor to keep the proof mass from moving far.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] The motor might be an electromagnet or in very small accelerometers, electrostatic.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Since the circuit's electronic behavior can be carefully designed, and the proof mass does not move far, these designs can be very stable (i.e. they do not oscillate), very linear with a controlled frequency response.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] In mechanical accelerometers, measurement is often electrical, piezoelectric, piezoresistive or capacitive.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Piezoelectric accelerometers use piezoceramic sensors (e.g. lead zirconate titanate) or single crystals (e.g. quartz, tourmaline).
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] They are unmatched in high frequency measurements, low packaged weight, and resistance to high temperatures.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Piezoresistive accelerometers resist shock (very high accelerations) better.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Capacitive accelerometers typically use a silicon micro-machined sensing element.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Modern mechanical accelerometers are often small *micro-electro-mechanical systems* (MEMS), and are often very simple MEMS devices, consisting of little more than a cantilever beam with a proof mass (also known as *seismic mass*).
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Damping results from the residual gas sealed in the device.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] As long as the Q-factor is not too low, damping does not result in a lower sensitivity.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Under the influence of external accelerations, the proof mass deflects from its neutral position.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] This deflection is measured in an analog or digital manner.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Most commonly, the capacitance between a set of fixed beams and a set of beams attached to the proof mass is measured.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] This method is simple, reliable, and inexpensive.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Integrating piezoresistors in the springs to detect spring deformation, and thus deflection, is a good alternative, although a few more process steps are needed during the fabrication sequence.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] For very high sensitivities quantum tunnelling is also used; this requires a dedicated process making it very expensive.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Optical measurement has been demonstrated in laboratory devices.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Another MEMS-based accelerometer is a thermal (or convective) accelerometer.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] It contains a small heater in a very small dome.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] This heats the air or other fluid inside the dome.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] The thermal bubble acts as the proof mass.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] An accompanying temperature sensor (like a thermistor; or thermopile) in the dome measures the temperature in one location of the dome.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] This measures the location of the heated bubble within the dome.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] When the dome is accelerated, the colder, higher density fluid pushes the heated bubble.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] The temperature measurement is interpreted as acceleration.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Gravity acting on the fluid provides the spring.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Since the proof mass is very lightweight gas, and not held by a beam or lever, thermal accelerometers can survive high shocks.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Another variation uses a wire to both heat the gas and detect the change in temperature.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] The change of temperature changes the resistance of the wire.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] A two dimensional accelerometer can be economically constructed with one dome, one bubble and two measurement devices.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Most micromechanical accelerometers operate *in-plane*, that is, they are designed to be sensitive only to a direction in the plane of the die.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] By integrating two devices perpendicularly on a single die a two-axis accelerometer can be made.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] By adding another *out-of-plane* device, three axes can be measured.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Such a combination may have much lower misalignment error than three discrete models combined after packaging.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Micromechanical accelerometers are available in a wide variety of measuring ranges, reaching up to thousands of *g*'s.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] The designer must compromise between sensitivity and the maximum acceleration that can be measured.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Accelerometers can be used to measure vehicle acceleration.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Accelerometers can be used to measure vibration on cars, machines, buildings, process control systems and safety installations.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] They can also be used to measure seismic activity, inclination, machine vibration, dynamic distance and speed with or without the influence of gravity.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Applications for accelerometers that measure gravity, wherein an accelerometer is specifically configured for use in gravimetry, are called gravimeters.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also increasingly used in the biological sciences.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] High frequency recordings of bi-axial or tri-axial acceleration allows the discrimination of behavioral patterns while animals are out of sight.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] For example, accelerometers have been used to study flight energy expenditure of Harris's Hawk (*Parabuteo unicinctus*).
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Researchers are also using smartphone accelerometers to collect and extract mechano-biological descriptors of resistance exercise.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Increasingly, researchers are deploying accelerometers with additional technology, such as cameras or microphones, to better understand animal behaviour in the wild (for example, hunting behaviour of Canada lynx).
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also used for machinery health monitoring to report the vibration and its changes in time of shafts at the bearings of rotating equipment such as turbines, pumps, fans, rollers, compressors, or bearing fault which, if not attended to promptly, can lead to costly repairs.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Accelerometer vibration data allows the user to monitor machines and detect these faults before the rotating equipment fails completely.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Accelerometers are widely used in structural health monitoring (SHM) of buildings, bridges and other civil infrastructure to record the dynamic response under ambient and forced loads (e.g., wind, traffic, machinery and earthquakes).
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] From these vibration records, engineers estimate modal properties—natural frequencies, damping ratios and mode shapes—often using operational modal analysis (OMA) techniques for in-service structures.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] These parameters are trended over time for condition assessment and model updating.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] In seismic regions, arrays of accelerometers installed in buildings and other structures provide strong-motion data for rapid post-event assessments and long-term performance studies.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Geological Survey's National Strong-Motion Project (NSMP) operates structural arrays and distributes building and structural records via the Center for Engineering Strong Motion Data (CESMD).
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Instrumentation and data-quality practices for building vibration measurements are guided by international standards.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] ISO 4866 provides principles for measuring the vibration of fixed structures and evaluating vibration effects based on structural response, while ISO 10137 gives serviceability recommendations for buildings and walkways with respect to human perception, contents and the structure itself.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Choice of accelerometer technology depends on frequency range and amplitude.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Piezoelectric accelerometers are common for higher-frequency, higher-amplitude measurements, whereas low-noise MEMS accelerometers have become attractive for low-frequency building and bridge monitoring and for dense or wireless deployments due to cost and power advantages.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Recent evaluations and developments show that appropriately selected MEMS devices can identify modal parameters with acceptable accuracy for SHM and have been integrated into high-sensitivity wireless nodes.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Networked and wireless smart-sensor approaches allow distributed monitoring at scale.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Reviews document the shift from wired to wireless SHM systems and the maturation of wireless smart-sensor networks for tasks such as ambient-vibration modal identification and continuous trending.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Accelerometers are often fused with other sensors to improve displacement and drift estimation, especially for large or flexible structures.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] GNSS provides quasi-static and very-low-frequency motion that complements accelerometer-based dynamics; recent studies report accurate dynamic displacement retrieval using high-rate or multi-GNSS solutions combined with accelerometers.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Beyond permanently instrumented assets, indirect and crowdsourced approaches using smartphone accelerometers have been explored, particularly for bridges.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Research has shown that modal frequencies—and in some cases spatial vibration characteristics—can be estimated from accelerometer data collected by vehicles crossing bridges, offering a complementary, low-cost screening tool for large inventories.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Related work has also evaluated smartphone-based ambient vibration monitoring of buildings.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Long-term case studies illustrate large-scale deployments.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Hong Kong's Wind and Structural Health Monitoring System (WASHMS) has instrumented the Tsing Ma Bridge since 1997; subsequent publications report decades of monitoring for load and response in service.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Scotland's Queensferry Crossing was equipped with a comprehensive SHM system including thousands of sensors, and Sydney Harbour Bridge has been reported as instrumented with thousands of sensors for real-time monitoring.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] SHM data are used for continuous condition tracking, event-triggered assessments (e.g., after earthquakes), and to support asset management decisions.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] In bridge engineering, guidance from transportation agencies describes how field data—including accelerometer measurements—can be integrated with inspection and nondestructive evaluation to improve load-rating reliability and maintenance planning.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Zoll's AED Plus uses CPR-D•padz which contain an accelerometer to measure the depth of CPR chest compressions.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Within the last several years, several companies have produced and marketed sports watches for runners that include footpods, containing accelerometers to help determine the speed and distance for the runner wearing the unit.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] In Belgium, accelerometer-based step counters are promoted by the government to encourage people to walk a few thousand steps each day.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Herman Digital Trainer uses accelerometers to measure strike force in physical training.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] It has been suggested to build football helmets with accelerometers in order to measure the impact of head collisions.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] The US Army Research Laboratory developed the Three-Axis Acceleration Switch which has been suggested for this application.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Accelerometers have been used to calculate gait parameters, such as stance and swing phase.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] This kind of sensor can be used to measure or monitor people.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] An inertial navigation system is a navigation aid that uses a computer and motion sensors (accelerometers) to continuously calculate via dead reckoning the position, orientation, and velocity (direction and speed of movement) of a moving object without the need for external references.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Other terms used to refer to inertial navigation systems or closely related devices include inertial guidance system, inertial reference platform, and many other variations.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] An accelerometer alone is unsuitable to determine changes in altitude over distances where the vertical decrease of gravity is significant, such as for aircraft and rockets.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] In the presence of a gravitational gradient, the calibration and data reduction process is numerically unstable.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used to detect apogee in both professional and in amateur rocketry.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also being used in Intelligent Compaction rollers.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used alongside gyroscopes in inertial navigation systems.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] One of the most common uses for MEMS accelerometers is in airbag deployment systems for modern automobiles.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] In this case, the accelerometers are used to detect the rapid negative acceleration of the vehicle to determine when a collision has occurred and the severity of the collision.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Another common automotive use is in electronic stability control systems, which use a lateral accelerometer to measure cornering forces.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] The widespread use of accelerometers in the automotive industry has pushed their cost down dramatically.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Another automotive application is the monitoring of noise, vibration, and harshness (NVH), conditions that cause discomfort for drivers and passengers and may also be indicators of mechanical faults.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Tilting trains use accelerometers and gyroscopes to calculate the required tilt.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Modern electronic accelerometers are used in remote sensing devices intended for the monitoring of active volcanoes to detect the motion of magma.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Accelerometers are increasingly being incorporated into personal electronic devices to detect the orientation of the device, for example, a display screen.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] A *free-fall sensor* (FFS) is an accelerometer used to detect if a system has been dropped and is falling.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] It can then apply safety measures such as parking the head of a hard disk to prevent a head crash and resulting data loss upon impact.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] This device is included in the many common computer and consumer electronic products that are produced by a variety of manufacturers.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] It is also used in some data loggers to monitor handling operations for shipping containers.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] The length of time in free fall is used to calculate the height of drop and to estimate the shock to the package.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Some smartphones, digital audio players and personal digital assistants contain accelerometers for user interface control; often the accelerometer is used to present landscape or portrait views of the device's screen, based on the way the device is being held.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Apple has included an accelerometer in every generation of iPhone, iPad, and iPod touch, as well as in every iPod nano since the 4th generation.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Along with orientation view adjustment, accelerometers in mobile devices can also be used as pedometers, in conjunction with specialized applications.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Automatic Collision Notification (ACN) systems also use accelerometers in a system to call for help in event of a vehicle crash.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Prominent ACN systems include OnStar AACN service, Ford Link's 911 Assist, Toyota's Safety Connect, Lexus Link, or BMW Assist.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Many accelerometer-equipped smartphones also have ACN software available for download.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] ACN systems are activated by detecting crash-strength accelerations.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used in vehicle Electronic stability control systems to measure the vehicle's actual movement.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] A computer compares the vehicle's actual movement to the driver's steering and throttle input.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] The stability control computer can selectively brake individual wheels and/or reduce engine power to minimize the difference between driver input and the vehicle's actual movement.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] This can help prevent the vehicle from spinning or rolling over.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Some pedometers use an accelerometer to more accurately measure the number of steps taken and distance traveled than a mechanical sensor can provide.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Nintendo's Wii video game console uses a controller called a Wii Remote that contains a three-axis accelerometer and was designed primarily for motion input.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Users also have the option of buying an additional motion-sensitive attachment, the Nunchuk, so that motion input could be recorded from both of the user's hands independently.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Is also used on the Nintendo 3DS system.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Sleep phase alarm clocks use accelerometric sensors to detect movement of a sleeper, so that it can wake the person when he/she is not in REM phase, in order to awaken the person more easily.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] A microphone or eardrum is a membrane that responds to oscillations in air pressure.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] These oscillations cause acceleration, so accelerometers can be used to record sound.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] A 2012 study found that voices can be detected in 93% of typical daily situations by accelerometers like those in smartphones fixed to the sternum.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Conversely, carefully designed sounds can cause accelerometers to report false data.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] One study tested 20 models of (MEMS) smartphone accelerometers and found that a majority were susceptible to this attack.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] A number of 21st-century devices use accelerometers to align the screen depending on the direction the device is held (e.g., switching between portrait and landscape modes).
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Such devices include many tablet PCs and some smartphones and digital cameras.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] The Amida Simputer, a handheld Linux device launched in 2004, was the first commercial handheld to have a built-in accelerometer.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] It incorporated many gesture-based interactions using this accelerometer, including page-turning, zoom-in and zoom-out of images, change of portrait to landscape mode, and many simple gesture-based games.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] As of January 2009, almost all new mobile phones and digital cameras contain at least a tilt sensor and sometimes an accelerometer for the purpose of auto image rotation, motion-sensitive mini-games, and correcting shake when taking photographs.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Camcorders use accelerometers for image stabilization, either by moving optical elements to adjust the light path to the sensor to cancel out unintended motions or digitally shifting the image to smooth out detected motion.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Some stills cameras use accelerometers for anti-blur capturing.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] The camera holds off capturing the image when the camera is moving.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] When the camera is still (if only for a millisecond, as could be the case for vibration), the image is captured.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] An example of the application of this technology is the Glogger VS2, a phone application which runs on Symbian based phones with accelerometers such as the Nokia N96.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Some digital cameras contain accelerometers to determine the orientation of the photo being taken and also for rotating the current picture when viewing.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Many laptops feature an accelerometer which is used to detect drops.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] If a drop is detected, the heads of the hard disk are parked to avoid data loss and possible head or disk damage by the ensuing shock.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] A gravimeter, or gravitometer, is an instrument used in gravimetry for measuring the local gravitational field.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] A gravimeter is a type of accelerometer, except that accelerometers are susceptible to all vibrations including noise, that cause oscillatory accelerations.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] This is counteracted in the gravimeter by integral vibration isolation and signal processing.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Though the essential principle of design is the same as in accelerometers, gravimeters are typically designed to be much more sensitive than accelerometers in order to measure very tiny changes within the Earth's gravity, of 1 *g*.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] In contrast, other accelerometers are often designed to measure 1000 *g* or more, and many perform multi-axial measurements.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] The constraints on temporal resolution are usually less for gravimeters, so that resolution can be increased by processing the output with a longer "time constant".
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] If done without a user's knowledge or consent, this is referred to as an inference attack.
[src:autothrottle/accelerometer] Additionally, millions of smartphones could be vulnerable to software cracking via accelerometers.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:autothrottle/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] An **adaptive compliant wing** is a wing which is flexible enough for aspects of its shape to be changed in flight.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] Flexible wings have a number of benefits.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] Conventional flight control mechanisms operate using hinges, resulting in disruptions to the airflow, vortices, and in some cases, separation of the airflow.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] These effects contribute to the drag of the aircraft, resulting in less efficiency and higher fuel costs.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] Flexible aerofoils can manipulate aerodynamic forces with less disruptions to the flow, resulting in less aerodynamic drag and improved fuel economy.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] Changing the shape of an aerodynamic surface has a direct effect on its aerodynamic properties.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] According to the flow condition and to the initial shape of the part, each shape variation (curvature, incidence, twist...) can have a different impact on the resulting forces and moments.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] This characteristic is actively pursued in adaptive wings which – by nature of their distributed compliance – can attain shape changes in a continuous, smooth, gap-free manner.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] By altering these geometrical parameters, the forces and moments can be modified, permitting to tailor them to the specific flight condition (e.g. for drag reduction) or to perform maneuvers (e.g. roll).
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] Shape adaptation can be classified according to the motion it enables.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] Changes of the airfoil shapes include altering its twist, and changing its camber and thickness distribution.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] An adaptive compliant wing designed by FlexSys Inc. features a variable-camber trailing edge which can be deflected up to ±10°, thus acting like a flap-equipped wing, but without the individual segments and gaps typical in a flap system.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] The wing itself can be twisted up to 1° per foot of span.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] The wing's shape can be changed at a rate of 30° per second, which is ideal for gust load alleviation.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] The development of the adaptive compliant wing is being sponsored by the U.S.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] Initially, the wing was tested in a wind tunnel, and then a 50-inch (1.3 m) section of wing was flight tested on board the Scaled Composites White Knight research aircraft in a seven-flight, 20-hour program operated from the Mojave Spaceport.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] Adaptive compliant wings are also investigated at ETH Zurich in the frame of the Smart airfoil project.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] The EU-funded Flexop program aims to develop to enable higher wing aspect ratio for less induced drag with lighter, more flexible airliner wings, along developing active flutter suppression for flexible wings.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] Partners include Hungary's MTA SZTAKI, Airbus, Austria's FACC, Inasco of Greece, Delft University of Technology, German aerospace center DLR, TUM, the UK's University of Bristol and RWTH Aachen University in Germany.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] On 19 November 2019, a 7 m (23 ft) span jet-powered UAV demonstrator with an aeroelastically tailored wing for passive load alleviation was flown in Oberpfaffenhofen, Germany, previously flown with a carbon-fiber, rigid wing to establish baseline performance.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] It has a conventional tube-and-wing configuration, unlike the blended wing body of the Lockheed Martin X-56.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] It follows the Grumman X-29 demonstrator in 1984, with more refined fiber orientations.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] The flexible wing is 4% lighter than the rigid one.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] The 54-month, €6.67 million ($7.4 million) project ends in November 2019, followed by the €3.85 million FLiPASED program from September 2019 until December 2022, using all the movable surfaces.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] The glass fiber flutter wing should to be flown in 2020, with unstable aeroelastic modes under 55 m/s (107 kn) that must be actively suppressed.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] With optimized aeroelastic tailoring and active flutter suppression, an aspect ratio of 12.4 could reduce fuel-burn by 5%, and 7% are targeted.
[src:autothrottle/adaptive-compliant-wing] FLiPASED is also led by MTA SZTAKI and include partners TUM, DLR and French aerospace research agency ONERA.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Modern aerodynamics only dates back to the seventeenth century, but aerodynamic forces have been harnessed by humans for thousands of years in sailboats and windmills, and images and stories of flight appear throughout recorded history including the Ancient Greek legend of Icarus and Daedalus.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Fundamental concepts of continuum, drag, and pressure gradients appear in the work of Aristotle and Archimedes.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] In 1726, Sir Isaac Newton became the first person to develop a theory of air resistance, making him one of the first aerodynamicists.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Dutch-Swiss mathematician Daniel Bernoulli followed in 1738 with *Hydrodynamica* in which he described a fundamental relationship between pressure, density, and flow velocity for incompressible flow known today as Bernoulli's principle, which provides one method for calculating aerodynamic lift.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] In 1757, Leonhard Euler published the more general Euler equations which could be applied to both compressible and incompressible flows.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The Euler equations were extended to incorporate the effects of viscosity in the first half of the 1800s, resulting in the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The Navier–Stokes equations are the most general governing equations of fluid flow but are difficult to solve for the flow around all but the simplest of shapes.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] In 1799, Sir George Cayley became the first person to identify the four aerodynamic forces of flight (weight, lift, drag, and thrust), as well as the relationships between them, and in doing so outlined the path toward achieving heavier-than-air flight for the next century.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] In 1871, Francis Herbert Wenham constructed the first wind tunnel, allowing precise measurements of aerodynamic forces.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Drag theories were developed by Jean Le Rond d'Alembert, Gustav Kirchhoff, and Lord Rayleigh.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] In 1889, Charles Renard, a French aeronautical engineer, became the first person to reasonably predict the power needed for sustained flight.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Otto Lilienthal, the first person to become highly successful with glider flights, was also the first to propose thin, curved airfoils that would produce high lift and low drag.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Building on these developments as well as research carried out in their own wind tunnel, the Wright brothers flew the first powered airplane on December 17, 1903.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] During the time of the first flights, Frederick W.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Lanchester, Martin Kutta, and Nikolai Zhukovsky independently created theories which connected circulation of a fluid flow to lift.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Kutta and Zhukovsky then developed a two-dimensional wing theory.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Expanding upon the work of Lanchester, Ludwig Prandtl is credited with developing the mathematics behind thin-airfoil and lifting-line theories as well as working with boundary layers.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] As aircraft speed increased designers began to encounter challenges associated with air compressibility at speeds near the speed of sound.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The differences in airflow under such conditions lead to problems in aircraft control, increased drag due to shock waves and the threat of structural failure due to aeroelastic flutter.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The ratio of the flow speed to the speed of sound was named the Mach number after Ernst Mach who was one of the first to investigate the properties of the supersonic flow.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Macquorn Rankine and Pierre Henri Hugoniot independently developed the theory for flow properties before and after a shock wave, while Jakob Ackeret led the initial work of calculating the lift and drag of supersonic airfoils.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Theodore von Kármán and Hugh Latimer Dryden introduced the term transonic to describe flow speeds between the critical Mach number and Mach 1 where drag increases rapidly.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The rapid increase in drag led aerodynamicists and aviators to disagree on whether supersonic flight was achievable until the sound barrier was broken in 1947 using the Bell X-1 aircraft.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] By the time the sound barrier was broken, aerodynamicists' understanding of the subsonic and low supersonic flow had matured.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The Cold War prompted the design of an ever-evolving line of high-performance aircraft.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Computational fluid dynamics began as an effort to solve for flow properties around complex objects and has rapidly grown to the point where entire aircraft can be designed using computer software, with wind-tunnel tests followed by flight tests to confirm the computer predictions.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Understanding of supersonic and hypersonic aerodynamics has matured since the 1960s, and the goals of aerodynamicists have shifted from the behaviour of fluid flow to the engineering of a vehicle such that it interacts predictably with the fluid flow.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Understanding the motion of air around an object (often called a flow field) enables the calculation of forces and moments acting on the object.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] In many aerodynamics problems, the forces of interest are the fundamental forces of flight: lift, drag, thrust, and weight.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Of these, lift and drag are aerodynamic forces, i.e. forces due to air flow over a solid body.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Calculation of these quantities is often founded upon the assumption that the flow field behaves as a continuum.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Continuum flow fields are characterized by properties such as flow velocity, pressure, density, and temperature, which may be functions of position and time.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] These properties may be directly or indirectly measured in aerodynamics experiments or calculated starting with the equations for conservation of mass, momentum, and energy in air flows.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Density, flow velocity, and an additional property, viscosity, are used to classify flow fields.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Flow velocity is used to classify flows according to speed regime.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Subsonic flows are flow fields in which the air speed field is always below the local speed of sound.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Transonic flows include both regions of subsonic flow and regions in which the local flow speed is greater than the local speed of sound.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Supersonic flows are defined to be flows in which the flow speed is greater than the speed of sound everywhere.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] A fourth classification, hypersonic flow, refers to flows where the flow speed is much greater than the speed of sound.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Aerodynamicists disagree on the precise definition of hypersonic flow.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Compressible flow accounts for varying density within the flow.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Subsonic flows are often idealized as incompressible, i.e. the density is assumed to be constant.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Transonic and supersonic flows are compressible, and calculations that neglect the changes of density in these flow fields will yield inaccurate results.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Viscosity is associated with the frictional forces in a flow.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] In some flow fields, viscous effects are very small, and approximate solutions may safely neglect viscous effects.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] These approximations are called inviscid flows.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Flows for which viscosity is not neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Finally, aerodynamic problems may also be classified by the flow environment.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] External aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes (e.g. around an airplane wing), while internal aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages inside solid objects (e.g. through a jet engine).
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Unlike liquids and solids, gases are composed of discrete molecules which occupy only a small fraction of the volume filled by the gas.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] On a molecular level, flow fields are made up of the collisions of many individual gas molecules among themselves, and their collisions with solid surfaces.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] However, in most aerodynamics applications, the discrete molecular nature of gases is ignored, and the flow field is assumed to behave as a continuum.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] This assumption allows fluid properties such as density and flow velocity to be defined everywhere within the flow.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The validity of the continuum assumption is dependent on the density of the gas and the application in question.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] For the continuum assumption to be valid, the mean free path length must be much smaller than the length scale of the application in question.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] For example, many aerodynamics applications deal with aircraft flying in atmospheric conditions, where the mean free path length is on the order of micrometers and where the body is orders of magnitude larger.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] In these cases, the length scale of the aircraft ranges from a few meters to a few tens of meters, which is much larger than the mean free path length.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] For such applications, the continuum assumption is reasonable.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The continuum assumption is less valid for extremely low-density flows like those encountered by vehicles at very high altitudes (e.g.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] 300,000 ft/90 km) or satellites in Low Earth orbit.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] In these cases, statistical mechanics is a more accurate method of solving the problem than is continuum aerodynamics.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The Knudsen number can be used to guide the choice between statistical mechanics and the continuous formulation of aerodynamics.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The assumption of a fluid continuum allows problems in aerodynamics to be solved using fluid dynamics conservation laws.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Together, the equations are known as Navier–Stokes equations, although some authors define the term to only include the momentum equation(s).
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Navier–Stokes equations have no known analytical solution and are solved in modern aerodynamics using computational techniques.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Because computational methods using high speed computers were not historically available and the high computational cost of solving these complex equations now that they are available, simplifications of the Navier–Stokes equations have been and continue to be employed.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Euler equations are a set of similar conservation equations which neglect viscosity and may be used in cases where the effect of viscosity is expected to be small.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Further simplifications lead to Laplace's equation and potential flow theory.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Additionally, Bernoulli's equation is a solution in one dimension to both the momentum and energy conservation equations.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The ideal gas law or another such equation of state is often used in conjunction with these equations to form a determined system which allows the solution for the unknown variables.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic problems are classified by the flow environment or properties of the flow, including flow speed, compressibility, and viscosity.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] *External* aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Evaluating the lift and drag on an airplane or the shock waves that form in front of the nose of a rocket are examples of external aerodynamics.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] *Internal* aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages in solid objects.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] For instance, internal aerodynamics encompasses the study of the airflow through a jet engine or through an air conditioning pipe.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic problems can also be classified according to whether the flow speed is below, near or above the speed of sound.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Aerodynamicists disagree over the precise definition of hypersonic flow; a rough definition considers flows with Mach numbers above 5 to be hypersonic.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The influence of viscosity on the flow dictates a third classification.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Some problems may encounter only very small viscous effects, in that case viscosity can be considered to be negligible.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The approximations to these problems are called inviscid flows.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Flows for which viscosity cannot be neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] An incompressible flow is a flow in which density is constant in both time and space.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Although all real fluids are compressible, a flow is often approximated as incompressible if the effect of the density changes cause only small changes to the calculated results.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] This is more likely to be true when the flow speeds are significantly lower than the speed of sound.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Effects of compressibility are more significant at speeds close to or above the speed of sound.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The Mach number is used to evaluate whether the incompressibility can be assumed, otherwise the effects of compressibility must be included.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Subsonic (or low-speed) aerodynamics describes fluid motion in flows which are much lower than the speed of sound everywhere in the flow.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] There are several branches of subsonic flow but one special case arises when the flow is inviscid, incompressible and irrotational.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] This case is called potential flow and allows the differential equations which describe the flow to be a simplified version of the equations of fluid dynamics, thus making available to the aerodynamicist a range of quick and easy solutions.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] In solving a subsonic problem, one decision to be made by the aerodynamicist is whether to incorporate the effects of compressibility.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Compressibility is a description of the amount of change of density in the flow.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] When the effects of compressibility on the solution are small, the assumption that density is constant may be made.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The problem is then an incompressible low-speed aerodynamics problem.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] When the density is allowed to vary, the flow is called compressible.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] In air, compressibility effects are usually ignored when the Mach number in the flow does not exceed 0.3 (about 335 feet (102 m) per second or 228 miles (366 km) per hour at 60 °F (16 °C)).
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Above Mach 0.3, the problem flow should be described using compressible aerodynamics.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] According to the theory of aerodynamics, a flow is considered to be compressible if the density changes along a streamline.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] This means that–unlike incompressible flow–changes in density are considered.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] In general, this is the case where the Mach number in part or all of the flow exceeds 0.3.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The Mach 0.3 value is rather arbitrary, but it is used because gas flows with a Mach number below that value demonstrate changes in density of less than 5%.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Furthermore, that maximum 5% density change occurs at the stagnation point (the point on the object where flow speed is zero), while the density changes around the rest of the object will be significantly lower.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Transonic, supersonic, and hypersonic flows are all compressible flows.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The term Transonic refers to a range of flow velocities just below and above the local speed of sound (generally taken as Mach 0.8–1.2).
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] It is defined as the range of speeds between the critical Mach number, when some parts of the airflow over an aircraft become supersonic, and a higher speed, typically near Mach 1.2, when all of the airflow is supersonic.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Between these speeds, some of the airflow is supersonic, while some of the airflow is not supersonic.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Supersonic aerodynamic problems are those involving flow speeds greater than the speed of sound.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Calculating the lift on the Concorde during cruise can be an example of a supersonic aerodynamic problem.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Supersonic flow behaves very differently from subsonic flow.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Fluids react to differences in pressure; pressure changes are how a fluid is "told" to respond to its environment.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Therefore, since sound is in fact, an infinitesimal pressure difference propagating through a fluid, the speed of sound in that fluid can be considered the fastest speed that "information" can travel in the flow.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] This difference most obviously manifests itself in the case of a fluid striking an object.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] In front of that object, the fluid builds up a stagnation pressure as impact with the object brings the moving fluid to rest.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] In fluid traveling at subsonic speed, this pressure disturbance can propagate upstream, changing the flow pattern ahead of the object and giving the impression that the fluid "knows" the object is there by seemingly adjusting its movement and is flowing around it.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] In a supersonic flow, however, the pressure disturbance cannot propagate upstream.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Thus, when the fluid finally reaches the object it strikes it and the fluid is forced to change its properties – temperature, density, pressure, and Mach number—in an extremely violent and irreversible fashion called a shock wave.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The presence of shock waves, along with the compressibility effects of high-flow velocity (see Reynolds number) fluids, is the central difference between the supersonic and subsonic aerodynamics regimes.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] In aerodynamics, hypersonic speeds are speeds that are highly supersonic.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] In the 1970s, the term generally came to refer to speeds of Mach 5 (5 times the speed of sound) and above.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The hypersonic regime is a subset of the supersonic regime.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Hypersonic flow is characterized by high temperature flow behind a shock wave, viscous interaction, and chemical dissociation of gas.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The incompressible and compressible flow regimes produce many associated phenomena, such as boundary layers and turbulence.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The concept of a boundary layer is important in many problems in aerodynamics.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The viscosity and fluid friction in the air is approximated as being significant only in this thin layer.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] This assumption makes the description of such aerodynamics much more tractable mathematically.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] In aerodynamics, turbulence is characterized by chaotic property changes in the flow.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] These include low momentum diffusion, high momentum convection, and rapid variation of pressure and flow velocity in space and time.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Flow that is not turbulent is called laminar flow.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Aerodynamics is a significant element of vehicle design, including road cars and trucks where the main goal is to reduce the vehicle drag coefficient, and racing cars, where in addition to reducing drag the goal is also to increase the overall level of downforce.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Aerodynamics is also important in the prediction of forces and moments acting on sailing vessels.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] It is used in the design of mechanical components such as hard drive heads.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Structural engineers resort to aerodynamics, and particularly aeroelasticity, when calculating wind loads in the design of large buildings, bridges, and wind turbines.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The aerodynamics of internal passages is important in heating/ventilation, gas piping, and in automotive engines where detailed flow patterns strongly affect the performance of the engine.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Urban aerodynamics are studied by town planners and designers seeking to improve amenity in outdoor spaces, or in creating urban microclimates to reduce the effects of urban pollution.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] The field of environmental aerodynamics describes ways in which atmospheric circulation and flight mechanics affect ecosystems.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic equations are used in numerical weather prediction.
[src:autothrottle/aerodynamics] Sports in which aerodynamics are of crucial importance include soccer, table tennis, cricket, baseball, and golf, in which most players can control the trajectory of the ball using the "Magnus effect".
[src:autothrottle/aft-pressure-bulkhead] The **aft pressure bulkhead** or **rear pressure bulkhead** is the rear component of the pressure seal in all aircraft that cruise in a tropopause zone in the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:autothrottle/aft-pressure-bulkhead] It helps maintain pressure when stratocruising and protects the aircraft from bursting due to the higher internal pressure.
[src:autothrottle/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Aft pressure bulkheads can either be curved, which reduces the amount of metal needed at the cost of reducing the usable space in the airliner, or flat, which gives more internal space but also more weight.
[src:autothrottle/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Patents have been filed that propose deliberately creating cavities within the rear bulkhead with the purpose of providing more usable cabin space.
[src:autothrottle/aft-pressure-bulkhead] On several airliners, production of the rear pressure bulkhead has been outsourced to third party manufacturers.
[src:autothrottle/aft-pressure-bulkhead] While typically being a time-consuming and somewhat uncommon process, an aircraft's aft pressure bulkhead can be wholly replaced.
[src:autothrottle/aft-pressure-bulkhead] During the twenty-first century, various parties became increasingly interested in developing aft pressure bulkheads composed from composite materials, seeking benefits such as lower manufacturing costs, easier sealing, elimination of corrosion risk, along with weight and part count reductions.
[src:autothrottle/aft-pressure-bulkhead] During the early 2000s, Airbus Group developed the largest manufactured resin film infusion structure then in production to function as the aft pressure bulkhead for their double-decker A380 airliner.
[src:autothrottle/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Multiple instances of damage to the aft pressure bulkhead have occurred; while a few cases have led to serious failures leading to aircraft losses, others have proven to be survivable.
[src:autothrottle/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Aviation certifying authorities have often mandated inspections of an aircraft's aft pressure bulkhead in the interest of safety.
[src:autothrottle/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Various techniques have been devised to determine the integrity of the rear pressure bulkhead; these have been used not only to inspect in-service examples but also in the design process, helping to design efficient bulkheads that possess sufficient strength to ensure a safe operational life.
[src:autothrottle/aft-pressure-bulkhead] In 1971, British European Airways Flight 706 crashed in Belgium, killing all 63 on board; the cause was determined to be corrosion of the rear pressure bulkhead by fluid contamination, perhaps from the lavatory.
[src:autothrottle/aft-pressure-bulkhead] The corrosion was not detectable by the inspection techniques at the time.
[src:autothrottle/aft-pressure-bulkhead] In 1985, Japan Air Lines Flight 123 crashed after a catastrophic failure of the aft pressure bulkhead.
[src:autothrottle/aft-pressure-bulkhead] The failure occurred due to faulty repair of the bulkhead after a tailstrike seven years earlier, when a single repair patch plate was incorrectly cut in two "to make it fit".
[src:autothrottle/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Failure of the bulkhead damaged hydraulic pipes passing through.
[src:autothrottle/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Boeing later calculated that the incorrect installation would be expected to fail after approximately 10,000 pressurizations; the repaired aircraft accomplished 12,318 successful flights before the crash.
[src:autothrottle/aft-pressure-bulkhead] During 2013, National Airlines Flight 102 crashed after loose freight on the main deck is believed to have penetrated the aft pressure bulkhead and caused damage to control systems in the vicinity of the bulkhead.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:autothrottle/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] An **aileron** (French for 'little wing' or 'fin') is a hinged flight control surface usually forming part of the trailing edge of each wing of a fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Ailerons are used in pairs to control the aircraft in roll (or movement around the aircraft's longitudinal axis), which normally results in a change in flight path due to the tilting of the lift vector.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Movement around this axis is called rolling or banking.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Considerable controversy exists over credit for the invention of the aileron.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The Wright brothers and Glenn Curtiss fought a years-long legal battle over the Wright patent of 1906, which described a method of wing-warping to achieve lateral control.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The brothers prevailed in several court decisions which found that Curtiss's use of ailerons violated the Wright patent.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Ultimately, the First World War compelled the U.S.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Government to legislate a legal resolution.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] A much earlier aileron concept was patented in 1868 by British scientist Matthew Piers Watt Boulton, based on his 1864 paper *On Aërial Locomotion*.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The name "aileron", from French, meaning "little wing", also refers to the extremities of a bird's wings used to control their flight.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] It first appeared in print in the 7th edition of Cassell's French-English Dictionary of 1877, with its lead meaning of "small wing".
[src:autothrottle/aileron] In the context of powered airplanes it appears in print about 1908.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Prior to that, ailerons were often referred to as rudders, their older technical sibling, with no distinction between their orientations and functions, or more descriptively as *horizontal rudders* (in French, *gouvernails horizontaux*).
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Among the earliest printed aeronautical use of 'aileron' was that in the French aviation journal *L'Aérophile* of 1908.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Ailerons had more or less completely supplanted other forms of lateral control, such as wing warping, by about 1915, well after the function of the rudder and elevator flight controls had been largely standardised.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] He was the first to patent an aileron control system in 1868.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Boulton's description of his lateral flight control system was "the first record we have of appreciation of the necessity for active lateral control as distinguished from [passive lateral stability]....
[src:autothrottle/aileron] With this invention of Boulton's we have the birth of the present-day three torque method of airborne control" as was praised by Charles Manly.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] 392 of 1868, issued about 35 years before ailerons were "reinvented" in France, became forgotten and lost from sight until after the flight control device was in general use.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Gibbs-Smith stated on several occasions that if the Boulton patent had been revealed at the time of the Wright brothers' legal filings, they might not have been able to claim priority of invention for the lateral control of flying machines.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The fact that the Wright brothers were able to gain a patent in 1906 did not invalidate Boulton's lost and forgotten invention.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The pioneering U.S. aeronautical engineer Octave Chanute published descriptions and drawings of the Wright brothers' 1902 glider in the leading aviation periodical of the day, *L'Aérophile*, in 1903.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] This prompted Esnault-Pelterie, a French military engineer, to build a Wright-style glider in 1904 that used ailerons in lieu of wing warping.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The French journal *L'Aérophile* then published photos of the ailerons on Esnault-Pelterie's glider which were included in his June 1905 article, and its ailerons were widely copied afterward.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The Wright brothers used wing warping instead of ailerons for roll control on their glider in 1902, and about 1904 their Flyer II was the only aircraft of its time able to do a coordinated banked turn.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] During the early years of powered flight the Wrights had better roll control on their designs than airplanes that used movable surfaces.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] From 1908, as aileron designs were refined it became clear that ailerons were much more effective and practical than wing warping.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Ailerons also had the advantage of not weakening the airplane's wing structure as did the wing warping technique, which was one reason for Esnault-Pelterie's decision to switch to ailerons.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] By 1911, most biplanes used ailerons rather than wing warping—by 1915, ailerons had become almost universal on monoplanes as well.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Government, frustrated by the lack of its country's aeronautical advances in the years leading up to World War I, enforced a patent pool effectively putting an end to the Wright brothers patent war.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The Wright company quietly changed its aircraft flight controls from wing warping to the use of ailerons at that time as well.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The Wright Brothers' Ohio patent attorney Henry Toulmin filed an expansive patent application and on May 22, 1906, the brothers were granted U.S.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The patent's importance lay in its claim of a new and useful method of *controlling* an airplane.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The patent application included the claim for the lateral control of aircraft flight that was not limited to wing warping, but through any manipulation of the "....angular relations of the lateral margins of the airplanes [wings].... varied in opposite directions".
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Thus the patent explicitly stated that other methods besides wing-warping could be used for adjusting the outer portions of an airplane's wings to different angles on its right and left sides to achieve lateral roll control.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Patent 831173 at nearly the same time for his methods of wing warping.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Both the Wright Brothers patent and Montgomery's patent were reviewed and approved by the same patent examiner at the United States Patent Office, William Townsend.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] At the time Townsend indicated that both methods of wing warping were invented independently and were sufficiently different to each justify their own patent award.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Multiple U.S. court decisions favoured the expansive Wright patent, which the Wright Brothers sought to enforce with licensing fees starting from $1,000 per airplane, and said to range up to $1,000 per day.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Casey, a former curator of the Smithsonian Air & Space Museum in Washington, D.C., and other researchers, due to the patent they had received the Wrights stood firmly on the position that all flying using lateral roll control, anywhere in the world, would only be conducted under license by them.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Years of protracted legal conflict ensued with many other aircraft builders until the U.S. entered World War I, when the government imposed a legislated agreement among the parties which resulted in royalty payments of 1% to the Wrights.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] There are still conflicting claims today over who first invented the aileron.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Other 19th century engineers and scientists, including Charles Renard, Alphonse Pénaud, and Louis Mouillard, had described similar flight control surfaces.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Another technique for lateral flight control, wing warping, was also described or experimented with by several people including Jean-Marie Le Bris, John Montgomery, Clement Ader, Edson Gallaudet, D.D.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Gibbs-Smith wrote that the aileron was "....one of the most remarkable inventions... of aeronautical history, which was immediately lost sight of".
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Ailerons are usually situated near the wing tip, but may sometimes also be situated nearer the wing root.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Modern airliners may also have a second pair of ailerons on their wings, with the two positions distinguished by the terms "outboard aileron" and "inboard aileron".
[src:autothrottle/aileron] An unwanted side effect of aileron operation is adverse yaw, a yawing moment in the opposite direction to the roll.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Using the ailerons to roll an aircraft to the right produces a yawing motion to the left.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] As the aircraft rolls, adverse yaw is caused partly by the change in drag between the left and right wing.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The rising wing generates increased lift, which causes increased induced drag.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The descending wing generates reduced lift, which causes reduced induced drag.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Profile drag caused by the deflected ailerons may add further to the difference, along with changes in the lift vectors as one rotates back while the other rotates forward.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] In a coordinated turn, adverse yaw is effectively compensated by the use of the rudder, which results in a sideforce on the vertical tail that opposes the adverse yaw by creating a favorable yawing moment.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Another method of compensation is "differential ailerons", which have been rigged so that the down-going aileron deflects less than the up-going one.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] In this case the opposing yaw moment is generated by a difference in profile drag between the left and right wingtips.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Ailerons may also be designed to use a combination of these methods.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] With ailerons in the neutral position, the wing on the outside of the turn develops more lift than the opposite wing due to the variation in airspeed across the wing span, which tends to cause the aircraft to continue to roll.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Once the desired angle of bank (degree of rotation about the longitudinal axis) has been obtained, the pilot uses opposite aileron to prevent the angle of bank from increasing due to this variation in lift across the wing span.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] This minor opposite use of the control must be maintained throughout the turn.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The pilot also uses a slight amount of rudder in the same direction as the turn to counteract adverse yaw and to produce a "coordinated" turn wherein the fuselage is parallel to the flight path.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] A simple gauge on the instrument panel called the slip indicator, also known as "the ball", indicates when this coordination is achieved.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Particularly on larger or faster aircraft, control forces may be extremely heavy.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Borrowing a discovery from boats that extending a control surface's area forward of the hinge lightens the forces needed first appeared on ailerons during World War I when ailerons were extended beyond the wingtip and provided with a horn ahead of the hinge.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Known as overhung ailerons, possibly the best known examples are the Handley Page Type O (first flight 17 December 1915), Sopwith Snipe, Fokker Dr.I and Fokker D.VII.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Later examples brought the counterbalance in line with the wing to improve control and reduce drag.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] This is seen less often now, due to the Frise type aileron which provides the same benefit.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Trim tabs are small movable sections resembling scaled down ailerons located at or near the trailing edge of the aileron.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] On most propeller powered aircraft, the rotation of the propellers induces a counteracting roll movement due to Newton's third law of motion, in that every action has an equal and opposite reaction.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] To relieve the pilot of having to provide continuous pressure on the stick in one direction, which causes fatigue, trim tabs are provided to adjust or *trim out* the pressure needed against any unwanted movement.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The tab itself is deflected in relation to the aileron, causing the aileron to move in the opposite direction.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Trim tabs come in two forms, adjustable and fixed.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] A fixed trim tab is manually bent to the required amount of deflection, while the adjustable trim tab can be controlled from within the cockpit so that different power settings or flight attitudes can be compensated for.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Some large aircraft from the 1950s (including the Canadair Argus) used free floating control surfaces that the pilot controlled only through the deflection of trim tabs, in which case additional tabs were also provided to fine-tune the control to provide straight and level flight.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Spades are flat metal plates, usually attached to the aileron lower surface, ahead of the aileron hinge, by a lever arm.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] They reduce the force needed by the pilot to deflect the aileron and are often seen on aerobatic aircraft.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] As the aileron is deflected upward, the spade produces a downward aerodynamic force, which tends to rotate the whole assembly so as to further deflect the aileron upward.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The size of the spade (and its lever arm) determines how much force the pilot needs to apply to deflect the aileron.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] A spade works in the same manner as a horn but is more effective due to the longer moment arm.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] To increase the speed at which control surface flutter (aeroelastic flutter) might become a risk, the center of gravity of the control surface is moved towards the hinge-line for that surface.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] To achieve this, lead weights may be added to the front of the aileron.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] In some aircraft the aileron construction may be too heavy to allow this system to work without an excessive increase in the weight of the aileron.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] In this case, the weight may be added to a lever arm to move the weight well out in front to the aileron body.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] These balance weights are tear drop shaped (to reduce drag), which make them appear quite different from spades, although both project forward and below the aileron.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] In addition to reducing the risk of flutter, mass balances also reduce the stick forces required to move the control surface in maneuvers.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Used during aviation's pre-war "pioneer era" and into the early years of the First World War, these ailerons were each controlled by a single cable, which pulled the aileron up.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] When the aircraft was at rest, the ailerons hung vertically down.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] This type of aileron was used on the Farman III biplane 1909 and the Short 166.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] A "reverse" version of this, utilizing wing-warping, existed on the later version of the Santos-Dumont *Demoiselle*, which only warped the wingtips "downward".
[src:autothrottle/aileron] One of the disadvantages of this setup was a greater tendency to yaw than even with basic interconnected ailerons.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] During the 1930s, a number of light aircraft used single acting controls but used springs to return the ailerons to their neutral positions when the stick was released.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The main problem with this type of aileron is the dangerous tendency to stall if used aggressively, especially if the aircraft is already in danger of stalling, hence the use primarily on prototypes, and their replacement on production aircraft with more conventional ailerons.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Engineer Leslie George Frise (1897–1979) of the Bristol Aeroplane Company developed an aileron shape that is pivoted at about its 25 to 30% chord line and near its bottom surface , in order to decrease stick forces as aircraft became faster during the 1930s.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] When the aileron is deflected up (to make its wing go down), the leading edge of the aileron starts to protrude below the underside of the wing into the airflow beneath the wing.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The moment of the leading edge in the airflow helps to move up the trailing edge, which decreases the stick force.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The down moving aileron also adds energy to the boundary layer.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The edge of the aileron directs air flow from the underside of the wing to the upper surface of the aileron, thus creating a lifting force added to the lift of the wing.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] This reduces the needed deflection of the aileron.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Both the Canadian Fleet Model 2 biplane of 1930 and the 1938 popular US Piper J-3 Cub monoplane possessed Frise ailerons as designed and helped introduce them to a wide audience.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] A claimed benefit of the Frise aileron is the ability to counteract adverse yaw.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] To do so, the leading edge of the aileron has to be sharp or bluntly rounded, which adds significant drag to the upturned aileron and helps counterbalance the yaw force created by the other aileron turned down.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] This can add some unpleasant, nonlinear effect and/or potentially dangerous aerodynamic vibration (flutter).
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Adverse yaw moment is basically countered by aircraft yaw stability and also by the use of differential aileron movement.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The Frise-type aileron also forms a slot, so air flows smoothly over the lowered aileron, making it more effective at high angles of attack.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Frise-type ailerons may also be designed to function differentially.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Like the differential aileron, the Frise-type aileron does not eliminate adverse yaw entirely.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Coordinated rudder application is still needed when ailerons are applied.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] By careful design of the mechanical linkages, the up aileron can be made to deflect more than the down aileron (e.g., US patent 1,565,097).
[src:autothrottle/aileron] This helps reduce the likelihood of a wing tip stall when aileron deflections are made at high angles of attack.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] In addition, the consequent differential in drag reduces adverse yaw (as also discussed above).
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The idea is that the loss of lift associated with the up aileron carries no penalty while the increase in lift associated with the down aileron is minimized.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The rolling couple on the aircraft is always the difference in lift between the two wings.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] A designer at de Havilland invented a simple and practical linkage and their de Havilland Tiger Moth classic British biplane became one of the best-known aircraft, and one of the earliest, to use differential ailerons.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] On the earliest Pioneer Era aircraft, such as the Wright Flyer and the later, 1909-origin Blériot XI and Etrich Taube, lateral control was effected by twisting the outboard portion of the wing so as to increase or decrease lift by changing the angle of attack.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] This had the disadvantages of stressing the structure, being heavy on the controls, and of risking stalling the side with the increased angle of attack during a maneuver.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] By 1916, most designers had abandoned wing warping in favor of ailerons.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Researchers at NASA and elsewhere have been taking a second look at wing warping again, although under new names.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The NASA version is the X-53 Active Aeroelastic Wing while the United States Air Force tested the Adaptive Compliant Wing.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Spoilers are devices that when extended into the airflow over a wing, disrupt the airflow and reduce the amount of lift generated.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Many modern aircraft designs, especially jet aircraft, use spoilers in lieu of, or to supplement ailerons, such as the F4 Phantom II and Northrop P-61 Black Widow, which had almost full width flaps (there were very small conventional ailerons at the wingtips as well).
[src:autothrottle/aileron] All aircraft with dihedral have some form of yaw-roll coupling to promote stability.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Common trainers like the Cessna 152/172 series can be roll controlled with rudder alone.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] The rudder of the Boeing 737 has more roll authority over the aircraft than the ailerons at high angles of attack.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] This led to two notable accidents when the rudder jammed in the fully deflected position causing rollovers (see Boeing 737 rudder issues).
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Some aircraft such as the Fokker Spin and model gliders lack any type of lateral control.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Those aircraft use a higher amount of dihedral than conventional aircraft.
[src:autothrottle/aileron] Deflecting the rudder gives yaw and a lot of differential wing lift, giving a yaw induced roll moment.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] An **autothrottle** (automatic throttle; also known as **autothrust**, **A/T**, or **A/THR**) is a system that allows a pilot to control the power setting of an aircraft's engines by specifying a desired flight characteristic, rather than manually controlling the fuel flow.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] The autothrottle can greatly reduce the pilots' workload and help conserve fuel and extend engine life by metering the precise amount of fuel required to attain a specific target indicated air speed, or the assigned power for different phases of flight.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] A/T and AFDS (Auto Flight Director Systems) can work together to fulfill the whole flight plan.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] There are two parameters that an A/T can maintain, or try to attain: speed and thrust.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] In speed mode the throttle is positioned to attain a set target speed, subject to safe operating margins.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] For example, if the pilot selects a target speed which is slower than stall speed, the autothrottle system maintains a speed above the stall speed.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] In the thrust mode the engine is maintained at a fixed power setting according to the different flight phases.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] For example, during takeoff, the A/T maintains constant takeoff power until takeoff mode is finished.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] During climb, the A/T maintains constant climb power; in descent, the A/T reduces the setting to the idle position, and so on.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] When the A/T is working in thrust mode, speed is controlled by pitch (or the control column), and not by the A/T.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] A radar altimeter feeds data to the autothrottle in this mode.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] On Boeing-type aircraft, A/T can be used in all flight phases from takeoff, climb, cruise, descent, approach, all the way to land or go-around, barring malfunction.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] Taxi is not considered a part of flight, and A/T does not work for taxiing.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] In most cases, A/T mode selection is automatic without the need of any manual selection unless interrupted by pilots.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] According to Boeing-published flight procedures, A/T is engaged before the takeoff procedure and is automatically disconnected two seconds after landing.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] During flight, manual override of A/T is always available.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] A release of manual override allows A/T to regain control, and the throttle will go back to the A/T commanded position except for two modes (Boeing type aircraft): IDLE and THR HLD.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] In these two modes, the throttle will remain at the manual commanded position.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] A primitive autothrottle was first fitted to later versions of the Messerschmitt Me 262 jet fighter late in World War II.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] However, the first commercial airplane with this system (named AutoPower) was the DC-3 (since 1956).
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] The first version was able to keep a constant angle of attack but speed-only during approach.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] When the possibility of maintaining speed during an entire flight was introduced, it led to the creation of the modern autothrottle.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] The RA-5C Vigilante used an autothrottle actuated by the input from accelerometers installed in the tail which caused the throttle to be sensitive to movement of the stabilator.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] This allowed the pilot to adjust the throttle setting during landing approach by stick input alone.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] Shortly after AutoPower's success, two companies, Sperry (now part of Honeywell) and Collins started competing in the development of an autothrottle, with more and more liners and business jets being equipped with it.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] Today, it is often linked to a flight management system.
[src:autothrottle/autothrottle] FADEC is an extension of the autothrottle concept and controls many other parameters besides fuel flow.
